recordings.rmk: Common Snipe calling in the vicinity of a perched male Cuckoo. The Common Snipe sounds consist mainly of 'whickering' rather than drumming. Actual drumming is not that loud but occurs for around two seconds after the eighth, eleventh and twentieth seconds. The Cuckoo was calling from the same perch for around three hours. As well as its main call, it was also occasionally uttering 'choking, gurgling' notes. The latter can be heard on this clip at 0:16, 0:21, 0:25, 0:28 and, after classic calling, at 0:50, 0:53 and 0:56. I was not present to observe the scene - but it sounds as though the Cuckoo may have uttered its gurgling notes in response to the presence of the Common Snipe - because it was piqued by the proximity of the Common Snipe's overhead drumming?

recordings.rmk:
The birds were in the area bordered by Husarviksvägen and Storra Skuggens väg.  The field has a ditch or stream running through it, but if I remember correctly, there were cattle in the field and a flock of Starling were also foraging there.

There was quite a lot of disturbance from traffic, joggers and even some horses. The birds were displaying visibly and singing for around 10 minutes, but much of the recording is ruined by the extraneous noise. During this period the birds did perform some flight displays, but my recording does not appear to have captured any flight calls.

This is another shorter extract from the 10 minute recording, which is relatively free from background noise.
